{"content": "Let's carefully re-calculate the sum \\( S = a_1 + a_2 + \\cdots + a_{100} \\), where \\( a_n = (-1)^{n+1}(3n + 2) \\).\n\nLet's compute the terms for odd and even \\( n \\):\n\n### For **odd** \\( n \\)\nLet \\( n = 2k-1 \\):\n- \\( (-1)^{(2k-1)+1} = (-1)^{2k} = 1 \\)\n- \\( a_{2k-1} = 1 \\cdot [3(2k-1) + 2] = 3(2k-1)+2 = 6k-3+2 = 6k-1 \\)\n\n### For **even** \\( n \\)\nLet \\( n = 2k \\):\n- \\( (-1)^{(2k)+1} = (-1)^{2k+1} = -1 \\)\n- \\( a_{2k} = -1 \\cdot [3(2k)+2] = -(6k+2) \\)\n\nSo,\n- \\( a_{2k-1} = 6k-1 \\)\n- \\( a_{2k}   = -(6k+2) \\)\n\n### Now, sum up:\nThere are 100 terms, so \\( k = 1 \\) to \\( 50 \\) for both odd and even indices.\n\n\\[\nS = \\sum_{k=1}^{50} a_{2k-1} + a_{2k}\n\\]\n\\[\nS = \\sum_{k=1}^{50} \\left[(6k-1) + (-(6k+2))\\right]\n\\]\n\\[\nS = \\sum_{k=1}^{50} \\left[(6k-1) - 6k - 2\\right]\n\\]\n", "in": 395, "out": 400}